## 6. Pros & Cons

- Pros
    - Exceptional balance of speed and spin, rivaling the absolute top tier of European/Japanese rubbers.
    - Very linear power delivery for a tensor, giving the player a strong sense of predictability.
    - Surprisingly good durability for an ESN rubber; the topsheet maintains its grip longer than many competitors.
- Cons
    - Can be slightly bouncy in the short game for players accustomed to dead, tacky Chinese rubbers.
    - The price point is relatively high, placing it in direct competition with the most established flagship rubbers.

---

## 7. Recommended Users & Pairings

- Who Should Buy This
    - Modern offensive players looking for a high-performance, non-tacky tensor.
    - Players transitioning from European to Chinese brands who want a familiar ESN feel but with DHS's design philosophy.
    - Aggressive loopers who rely on speed and high spin from both wings.
- Who Should Avoid This
    - Beginners who need slower, highly controlled equipment to learn basic strokes.
    - Traditional Chinese rubber purists who rely on extreme tackiness and zero-bounce for their short game.
- Complementary Rubber Pairings (Opposite Side)
    - If used on FH: Pair with a softer, highly controllable rubber on the BH (e.g., Nittaku Fastarc C-1 or a softer Gold Arc 8).
    - If used on BH: Pair with a classic tacky rubber on the FH (e.g., DHS Hurricane 3 Neo) for the ultimate hybrid setup.

---

## 8. Value & Alternatives

- Value Verdict
    - High value. While priced in the premium tier, its durability and top-end performance justify the cost for serious competitive players.
- Similar Alternatives
    - Same Brand: DHS Gold Arc 5 (softer, slower, more control-oriented).
    - Rival Brand: Tibhar Evolution MX-P (similar power and click), Yasaka Rakza 7 (similar grip and reliability), Butterfly Tenergy 05 (similar top-end spin, though T05 has a higher arc).
- Closest Feel Match Summary
    - Plays very much like a slightly more durable, slightly more linear Tibhar Evolution MX-P or a modern generation Yasaka Rakza.

